text:
"Gattaca" is among the most underrated films ever. Ethan Hawke has said in recent interviews that the movie he still gets approached about the most is Gattica. Everyone should see that film. Wonderful! Underdog story.

"Prisoners" is also super solid. That is acting 101. My gosh that movie is edge of your seat material from beginning to end. Hugh Jackman's best performance in my opinion. Gyllenhall and Paul Dano are exceptional. 

"A Simple Plan" is a masterpiece! I'm dead serious, you will not see better acting. That movie is intriguing, upsetting, emotional and entirely thought provoking. That is the best movie Bill Paxton and/or Billy Bob Thornton have ever made. I've watched it at least 8 times. Both Bill Paxton and Billy Bob should have been nominated for an award. Career highlights for both. Rest in peace, Bill Paxton. Top 25 all time for me.

text: Great list. Kiiss Bang Bang is a blast. A Simple Plan is excellent. The King of Comedy is more layered than After Hours. After Hours is good,, primarily quirky. Jerry Lewis turns in a masterful performance in The King of Comedy as an obnoxious & thoroughly unlikable character.  Blow Our is one of my favorite films. John Travolta's acting is so understated yet powerful. It is easily one of his best performances. Nancy Allen character is initially a brassy blonde involved in shady PI racket setting up married men. It evolves to a more fragile  one. John Lithgow is so frakking creepy. This is his precursor to the Trinity killer on Dexter. His casual brutality as an assassin is chilling. The movie has great pacing; it leads to an emotional crescendo. I've seen it so  many times yet I always sob at the end.

text: ¬†@Christian Zafiroglu¬† Thank you for your response.  I feel as if only Duvall could have made the film.  Most of Hollywood is ignorant, ambivalent, or even hostile to the evangelical/Pentecostal/charismatic "subculture." Had the film been made by said religious community itself it would have been a propaganda piece devoid of the complexities of plot, personality, and human experience.  Duvall, being a sympathetic observer, is able to avoid both overly simplistic extremes.  His character is deeply flawed but his desire to communicate with the divine even in his folksy way is transcendent.

text:
Good choice with Matchstick Men. I would also have included The Weather Man.
1. Let the Right One In--Both Versions
2. Hannah
3. Matrix: Reloaded--For the sheer bravado of its action pieces
4. Mother Night--Excellent adaptation of one of Kurt Vonnegut's best books, and Nick Nolte gives a fantastic performance. 
5. Jackass: The Movie--This was before reviewers and critics understood what was really going on in these movies. It received 48% on Rotten Tomatoes. Jackass 2 and 3 increased that number fully 20%. And Jackass Forever received a shocking 85% positive rating. 
6. The Duelists--Ridley Scott's first film I believe. Although he has made some stinkers, I can still call him my favorite director. 
7. Black Hawk Down--Yes I know it received accolades, but I believe it could be the most intense and well-paced representation of Americans in combat. 
8. Unbreakable--The first great "superhero film," back when Shyamalan still had "the touch."
9. Her--the Jackass co-creator Spike Jonze has extraordinary hidden depths. He's directed 4 movies, all of them masterpieces to my mind. Her is one of the most poignant, affecting movies I've ever seen. He also made the Weezer "Happy Days" video. 
10. Copland--Not just one of Sylvester Stallone's best performances, it's rather a stunning performance. Strong story, with excellent direction by James Mangold.
